solution.p:
We factor each numerator and denominator, and look for common factors. 
    \amp \dfrac{4y^2-1}{4-y^2} \cdot \dfrac{y^2-2y}{4y+2} \amp 
        \amp\qquad=\dfrac{(2y-1)\cancel{(2y+1)}}{\cancel{(2-y)}(2+y)} \cdot \dfrac{y(-1)\cancel{(y-2)}}{2\cancel{(2y+1)}} \amp \amp \blert{\text{Divide out common factors.}}
        \amp\qquad = \dfrac{-y(2y-1)}{2(y+2)} \amp \amp \blert{\text{Note:}~~y-2=-(2-y)}

We multiply the first fraction by the reciprocal of the second fraction.  
    \dfrac{6ab}{2a+b} \div (4a^2b) \amp = \dfrac{\blert{\cancel{2} \cdot 3}\cancel{ab}}{2a+b} \cdot \dfrac{1}{\blert{\cancel{2} \cdot 2}a \cdot \cancel{ab}} \amp \amp \blert{\text{Divide out common factors.}}
         \amp = \dfrac{3}{2a(2a+b)}

Step 2:  We build each fraction to an equivalent one with the LCD.
     \dfrac{3x\alert{(x-3)}}{(x+2)\alert{(x-3)}} = \dfrac{3x^2-9x}{x^2-x-6}~~~~\text{and}~~~~\dfrac{2x\alert{(x+2)}}{(x-3)\alert{(x+2)}} = \dfrac{2x^2+4x}{x^2-x-6}
Step 3:  Combine the numerators over the same denominator.
    \dfrac{3x}{x+2} - \dfrac{2x}{x-3} \amp = \dfrac{3x^2-9x}{x^2-x-6}-\dfrac{2x^2+4x}{x^2-x-6}  
        \amp = \dfrac{(3x^2-9x)-(2x^2+4x)}{x^2-x-6} \amp \amp \blert{\text{Subtract the numerators.}}
         \amp = \dfrac{x^2-13x}{x^2-x-6} 
Step 4:  Reduce the result, if possible.  We factor numerator and denominator to find
    \dfrac{x(x-13)}{(x-3)(x+2)}
The fraction cannot be reduced.

Step 2:  We build each fraction to an equivalent one with the LCD.
     1=\dfrac{1\cdot\alert{a(a+1)}}{1\cdot\alert{a(a+1)}} \amp = \dfrac{a^2+a}{a(a+1)}
         \dfrac{2}{a}=\dfrac{2\cdot\alert{(a+1)}}{a\cdot\alert{(a+1)}} \amp = \dfrac{2a+2}{a(a+1)}
        \dfrac{a^2+2}{a^2+a}  \amp = \dfrac{a^2+2}{a(a+1)}
Step 3:  Combine the numerators over the same denominator.
    1+\dfrac{2}{a}-\dfrac{a^2+2}{a^2+a} \amp =\dfrac{a^2+a}{a(a+1)}+\dfrac{2a+2}{a(a+1)}-\dfrac{a^2+2}{a(a+1)}
        \amp = \dfrac{(a^2+a)+(2a+2)-(a^2+2)}{a(a+1)} =\dfrac{3a}{a(a+1)}
Step 4:  Reduce the fraction to find
    \dfrac{3\cancel{a}}{\cancel{a}(a+1)} = \dfrac{3}{a+1}

Consider all the simple fractions that appear in the complex fraction; in this case their LCD is 4. We multiply each term of the numerator and each term of the denominator by 4.
    \dfrac{\alert{4}\left(x+\dfrac{3}{4}\right)} {\alert{4}\left(x-\dfrac{1}{2}\right)} =\dfrac{\alert{4}(x)+\alert{4}\left(\dfrac{3}{4}\right)}{\alert{4}(x)-\alert{4}\left(\dfrac{1}{2}\right)} = \dfrac{4x+3}{4x-2}
The original complex fraction is equivalent tp the simple fraction \dfrac{4x+3}{4x-2}.
